Coming to terms with having your last baby is such a hard decision. Some people just know that they are done…. some people are stuck somewhere in the middle. I feel like I’m still in a position where I feel stuck.

I love having babies and raising little humans, but truthfully, I know it won’t be possible. My health cannot handle another baby. My wallet cannot handle another baby. My family who has cared for my other kids… it would be too much for them.

The list can go on, and there’s so many other reasons why people are done having babies. Traumatic birth. Infertility. Financial issues. Childcare. I could keep going and the list would be so long.

Closing this chapter is very very difficult for me. I wish I could hold everyone one my babies for the first time again. When I tell you, there’s nothing like that feeling…. At least for me there isn’t. 

I know there is so much to look forward to in the future. There are so many things they are gonna do! It does not make it any easier! Solidarity mamas & thanks for letting me rant 😭😂

5 tips for colder weather (bedtime addition).

Keep the thermostat between 68°-72°F. This is deemed the safest and most comfortable temperature range for infants by The American Association of Pediatrics. Too warm of room temperatures, along with warm clothing can be dangerous.
Make sure to check the windows and doors for drafts. Move your baby’s crib away from drafty areas. For drafty windows, consider putting up a shade to block the draft.
Keep your baby in one extra layer than yourself. I love layering in colder weather in general. I think that’s the best way to keep warm during winter months. I suggest using the gently weighted sleep sack by Smooch over your baby’s pajamas. I love this sleep sack for many reasons. 
It is made out of organic cotton so the fabric is both warm and breathable. I am blown away by how good the quality is. It is definitely worth the money.
The gentle weight is located on the top of the sleep sack and promotes self soothing and calming by mimicking your touch - so your baby feels comforted and supported while they sleep.
Ever since using it, my baby has been sleeping for longer periods of time at night and during nap-time. It is definitely a game changer.
The two-way zipper makes middle of the night diaper changes so easy and convenient. I don’t have to take off the whole sleep sack to change my baby’s diaper.

4. Get a cool mist humidifier. This helps add moisture to winter’s dry air. It’s also nice at helping your baby breathe better if he catches a cold.

5. Last, but not least. Water, along with cold temperatures and a lack of humidity, can cause your baby to get dry skin. Here’s how you can help your baby’s skin stay soft and moist:
Limit your baby’s bath-time to about 5-10 minutes.
After the bath, make sure your baby is completely dry.
Apply a good moisturizer before dressing your baby. You can apply it multiple times a day if necessary.
Choose a lotion or ointment that locks in the moisture.
